Characteristics of a RESTful API

REST (Representational State Transfer) is an architectural style with specific rules.
An API is considered RESTful only if it follows these principles:

âœ… 1. Stateless

Most important rule.
Server does not store client session or context.
Every request must contain all needed information.
The server treats every request as independent.

â¡ï¸ No session, no JSESSIONID, no server memory â†’ pure REST
â¡ï¸ Uses JWT/OAuth tokens, not cookies.

âœ… 2. Clientâ€“Server Separation
The client (frontend/UI) and server (backend/API) must be independent.
Client handles UI logic
Server handles data/business logic
Both can develop independently

âœ… 3. Uniform Interface
REST API must use consistent patterns:
ğŸ”¹ Resource-based URLs (nouns, not verbs)
âœ” /users
âœ” /users/10/orders

âŒ /getUsers
âŒ /createUser

ğŸ”¹ HTTP methods follow CRUD:
Operation	HTTP Method
Create	POST
Read	GET
Update	PUT/PATCH
Delete	DELETE
ğŸ”¹ Proper use of HTTP status codes

Examples:

200 (OK)
201 (Created)
400 (Bad Request)
401/403 (Authentication/Authorization)
404 (Not Found)
500 (Server error)
503(Service Unavailable)

âœ… 4. Cacheable
REST should leverage caching for performance.
Server indicates if responses can be cached using headers:
Cache-Control: max-age=3600


Helps reduce load and speed up responses.
âœ… 5. Layered System

The client should not know whether it's connected to:
Main server
Load balancer
Proxy
Authentication server
Architecture can have multiple layers, but the client sees it as one.

âœ… 6. Resource Representation

Data is treated as resources, not actions.

Resources must be represented in a standard format, commonly:

JSON (most common)
XML
HTML
YAML

Example:

{
  "id": 10,
  "name": "John"
}

âœ… 7. HATEOAS (Optional in modern APIs)

Hypermedia as the Engine of Application State â€” links inside JSON pointing to next possible actions.

Example:

{
  "user": 10,
  "name": "John",
  "links": [
     { "rel": "orders", "href": "/users/10/orders" }
  ]
}


Not strictly used in modern APIs, but part of REST theory.

â­ Summary Table (Quick Revision)
Characteristic	Meaning
Stateless	No session stored, each request independent
Clientâ€“Server	Separation of UI & backend
Uniform Interface	Resource-based URLs + HTTP methods
Cacheable	Uses caching for performance
Layered system	Multiple layers allowed
Resource Representation	JSON/XML-based resources
HATEOAS	Links inside responses (optional)
â­ How to identify a RESTful API?

If the API uses:
âœ” Tokens instead of sessions
âœ” Resource-based URLs
âœ” Stateless communication
âœ” Standard HTTP methods
âœ” Standard HTTP response codes

â¡ï¸ Then it is RESTful